'''Executive Action''' is a term that may have been used by the [[Central Intelligence Agency]] starting in the early 1950s. It refers to [[Human rights violations by the CIA#Assassinations|assassination operations]].<ref>Escalante Font, Fabián. Executive Action: 634 Ways to Kill Fidel Castro. Melbourne: Ocean Press, 2006.</ref> It is said that these operations may have been conducted by the CIA's [[Division D]], a subsection of the agency's Directorate of Operations.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Strength of the Wolf: The Secret History of America's War on Drugs|last=Valentine|first=Douglas|publisher=Verso|year=2004|isbn=9781859845684|location=|pages=226}}</ref> A possible list of "Executive Action" operations may include an attempt to kill [[Fidel Castro]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1975/10/04/archives/cia-assassination-unit-described.html|title=C.I.A. Assassination Unit Described|last=|first=|date=October 1975|website=The New York Times|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref> using a cigar injected with [[Botulism]] toxin<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-cuba-cia-idUSN0427935120070705|title=Closest CIA bid to kill Castro was poisoned drink|last=Boadle|first=Anthony|date=July 2007|website=Reuters|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref> and an alleged plan to kill rebel leader [[Che Guevara]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fordlibrarymuseum.gov/library/document/0005/7324009.pdf|title=Summary of Facts Investigation of CIA Involvement in Plans to Assassinate Foreign Leaders|last=|first=|date=June 1975|website=Gerald R. Ford Presidential Library & Museum|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref>

The [[Ford administration]] forbade assassination in 1976 with [[Executive Order 11905]].  A ''[[Washington Post]]'' article, c. 1989{{citation needed|date=July 2014}}{{Verify source|date=January 2010}}, may have reported that a "secret" ruling of the [[U.S. Department of State]]'s Office of Legal Advisor had interpreted that Ford's Executive Order only banned ''intentional'' killings of foreign leaders, thus clearing the way for "accidental" killings of foreign leaders; for example, during the confusion of a coup or invasion. Since this ruling was one of at least four preceding the [[United States invasion of Panama|U.S. invasion of Panama]], some{{Who|date=January 2010}} saw the ruling as giving a green light for [[Manuel Noriega]] to be killed "accidentally". Noriega survived the invasion and surrendered to US forces.

The CIA started to use [[UAVs in the U.S. military|drone strikes]] for [[targeted killing]] under President [[George W. Bush]] in 2001, during the [[War on Terror]].<ref>[https://www.theatlantic.com/international/archive/2015/05/america-first-drone-strike-afghanistan/394463/ The Story of America's Very First Drone Strike]</ref> It lost authority to do so by order of President [[Barack Obama]], but regained it again under President [[Donald Trump]].<ref>[https://www.npr.org/2017/03/14/520162910/trump-restores-cia-power-to-launch-drone-strikes Trump Restores CIA Power To Launch Drone Strikes]</ref>

