{{Infobox Mayor | name=Woodrow Wilson Mann | office=[[List of mayors of Little Rock, Arkansas|Mayor of Little Rock, Arkansas]] | party=[[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] | term_start=January 1, 1956 | term_end=December 31, 1957 | preceded=[[Pratt C. Remmel]] | succeeded=[[Werner C. Knoop]] | birth_date={{Birth date|1916|11|13}} | birth_place=[[Little Rock, Arkansas|Little Rock]], [[Arkansas]], USA | death_date={{death date and age|2002|8|6|1916|11|13}} | death_place=[[Houston, Texas|Houston]], [[Texas]] | resting_place=Memorial Oaks Cemetery in Houston | occupation=[[Insurance agent]] | spouse= Beverly Mann | children=1 | religion= | alma_mater=[[University of Illinois]] | branch=[[United States Navy]] | battles=[[World War II]] | footnotes= | awards= }}
'''Woodrow Wilson Mann''' (November 13, 1916 &ndash; August 6, 2002) was an [[United States|American]] politician who was the [[mayor]] of the capital city of [[Little Rock, Arkansas|Little Rock]], [[Arkansas]], from 1956 to 1957.
A Little Rock native, Mann attended the [[University of Illinois]] and fought in [[World War II]] with the [[United States Navy]] in the [[Asiatic-Pacific Theater|Pacific Theater of Operations]]. He was a member of the staff of Admiral [[Chester Nimitz]]. Upon his return to the United States, he established an insurance agency.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2002/08/09/us/woodrow-mann-dies-at-85-sought-troops-in-little-rock.html]</ref> A [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]], Mann unseated Mayor [[Pratt C. Remmel]], a two-term [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]], in the 1955 municipal election and took office on January 1, 1956.
The [[Little Rock Nine]] [[Segregation in the United States|school desegregation]] case occurred near the end of Mann's term as mayor in 1957. Outraged by [[governor of Arkansas|Governor]] [[Orval Faubus]]' order that [[National Guard of the United States|National Guard]] troops block the entrance of the students at [[Little Rock Central High School]], Mann sent a telegram to President [[Dwight D. Eisenhower]] to request federal troops. Eisenhower soon authorized the troops. After his term as mayor, Mann moved in 1960 to [[Houston]], [[Texas]], where he died in 2002<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/news/2002/aug/31/guardianobituaries.usa</ref><ref>http://articles.latimes.com/2002/aug/10/local/me-mann10]</ref> and is interred at Memorial Oaks Cemetery.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.findagrave.com/cgi-bin/fg.cgi?page=gr&GSln=Mann&GSfn=Woodrow&GSmn=Wilson&GSbyrel=all&GSdyrel=all&GSob=n&GRid=7060622&df=all&|title=Woodrow Wilson Mann|publisher=Findagrave.com|accessdate=August 10, 2017}}</ref>
